{"id":"2008.05322","submitter":"Claudiu Costin","authors":"Claudiu Costin","title":"Secondary electron emission under magnetic constraint: from Monte Carlo\n  simulations to analytical solution","comments":"peer-reviewed version of the manuscript published in Scientific\n  Reports","journal-ref":"Scientific Reports 11 (2021) 1874","doi":"10.1038/s41598-021-81345-x","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.plasm-ph physics.comp-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The secondary electron emission process is essential for the optimal\noperation of a wide range of applications, including fusion reactors,\nhigh-energy accelerators, or spacecraft. The process can be influenced and\ncontrolled by the use of a magnetic field. An analytical solution is proposed\nto describe the secondary electron emission process in an oblique magnetic\nfield. It was derived from Monte Carlo simulations. The analytical formula\ncaptures the influence of the magnetic field magnitude and tilt, electron\nemission energy, electron reflection on the surface, and electric field\nintensity on the secondary emission process. The last two parameters increase\nthe effective emission while the others act the opposite. The electric field\neffect is equivalent to a reduction of the magnetic field tilt. A very good\nagreement is shown between the analytical and numerical results for a wide\nrange of parameters. The analytical solution is a convenient tool for the\ntheoretical study and design of magnetically assisted applications, providing\nrealistic input for subsequent simulations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 11 Aug 2020 12:25:05 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 9 Sep 2020 11:40:56 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 25 Sep 2020 14:03:09 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 2 Feb 2021 15:07:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-02-03"}
